[3] USA (Ohio)
Date: Tue 9 Sep 2014
Source: Daily Journal, Associated Press Report [abridged, edited]
http://www.dailyjournal.net/view/story/78f17758774942db88ac74b5846319f8/OH--Measles-Ohio/


The Ohio outbreak that helped push the annual number of U.S. measles cases to its highest total since 1996 appears to have ended, according to state health officials. The state logged 377 cases of the highly contagious viral respiratory illness in 9 counties since March 2014 in the outbreak, and 9 people were hospitalised. The end of such an outbreak is measured 42 days after the onset of the most recent case, a window based on 2, 21-day incubation periods. Ohio has passed that mark because the most recent onset date was 23 Jul 2014.

"In [a viral disease] like this, it could appear anytime, so we're not looking to say it's over," Ohio Department of Health spokeswoman Melanie Amato said. "We're just saying the incubation period has passed, so it's a great sign that measles has moved on."

Health officials determined the Ohio outbreak started among Amish in Knox County who had traveled to the Philippines, which has had a measles epidemic. At least 592 measles cases have been reported in the United States this year [2014], and many of those cases have a connection to the Philippines, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

[Byline: Kantele Franko]

