[4] USA (Seattle International Airport)
Date: Sat 13 Sep 2014
Source: The B-Town Blog [abridged, edited]
http://b-townblog.com/2014/09/13/confirmed-case-of-measles-reported-at-sea-tac-airport/


Local public health officials are investigating a confirmed case of measles infection in a traveler who was at Sea-Tac Airport [Seattle International airport] during the contagious period. The traveler was likely exposed to measles outside of the United States.

Most people in our area have immunity to the measles through vaccination, so the risk to the general public is low. However, all persons who were in the following locations around the same time as the individual with measles should: Find out whether they have been vaccinated for measles or have had measles previously; Call a health care provider promptly if they develop an illness with fever or illness with an unexplained rash between 13-27 Sep 2014. To avoid possibly spreading measles to other patients, do not go to a clinic or hospital without calling 1st to tell them you want to be evaluated for measles.

Before receiving the measles diagnosis, the traveler was at Sea-Tac Airport and the Courtyard Seattle Federal Way Hotel's restaurant, The Bistro. Anyone who was at Sea-Tac Airport or The Bistro during the following times was possibly exposed to measles. [The times can be determined by accessing the original report at the source URL]. If you were at either of these locations during the times listed and are not immune to measles, the most likely time you would become sick is between 13-27 Sep 2014.

Measles symptoms begin 7 to 21 days after exposure. Measles is contagious from approximately 4 days before the rash appears through 4 days after the rash appears. People can spread measles before they have the characteristic measles rash. People at highest risk from exposure to measles include those who are unvaccinated, pregnant women, infants under 6 months of age and those with weakened immune systems.

