[6] Taiwan (Travel alert)
Date: Tue 9 Sep 2014
Source: China Times, CNA [edited]
http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20140909000006&cid=1103


People planning to travel to China or Southeast Asia should take precautions against measles amid a surging number of cases of the viral infection being reported in those regions, Taiwan's Centers for Disease Control (CDC) said on Monday [8 Sep 2014]. Taiwan confirmed the year's [2014] 19th case last week in a 24-year-old man who had visited the Philippines in mid-August 2014, the CDC said. Besides that Southeast Asian country, cases have been reported in China, Indonesia, Malaysia and Viet Nam, the CDC said, urging travelers to these areas to pay close attention to their personal hygiene.

In China, the Philippines and Viet Nam, the epidemic is especially severe this year [2014] compared with 2013, the CDC warned, adding that there have been tens of thousands of cases documented in the 3 countries. Travelers to affected areas should seek medical treatment if they develop symptoms such as fever, nasal inflammation or rash, the CDC said.

The measles virus infects the respiratory system, immune system and skin. Symptoms usually occur 7 to 14 days after exposure to an infected person.

